---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import LessonNav from "../../components/LessonNav.astro";
import SeeAlso from "../../components/SeeAlso.astro";
import MeshSimulator from "../../components/MeshSimulator";
import BloomFilterViz from "../../components/BloomFilterViz";
import RoutingDemo from "../../components/RoutingDemo";
import Quiz from "../../components/Quiz";
import { getQuiz } from "../../data/quizzes";
---

<Base title="Spanning Tree & Routing">
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <p class="text-fips-accent font-mono text-sm mb-2">Lesson 5</p>
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">Spanning Tree & Routing</h1>

    <section class="space-y-4 text-fips-text leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        Routing in FIPS has no central routing table. Each node makes local forwarding decisions
        using three data structures: a spanning tree, a set of bloom filters, and a coordinate
        system derived from the tree. Together, these let any node forward a packet toward any other
        node, using only information it already has from its direct peers.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Building the spanning tree</h2>

      <p>
        Every FIPS mesh has a root. The root is the node with the lexicographically smallest <code
          class="mono text-fips-accent">node_addr</code
        >. No election protocol is needed. Each node picks the smallest address it has heard about,
        and because the sorting is deterministic, all nodes converge on the same root.
      </p>

      <p>
        Each node selects one of its peers as a parent. The parent is the peer that offers the best
        path to the root, weighted by link cost (measured via MMP: round-trip time, loss rate,
        jitter). The resulting parent-child relationships form a spanning tree over the mesh.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Coordinates</h2>

      <p>
        A node's tree coordinate is the sequence of <code class="mono text-fips-accent"
          >node_addr</code
        > values from itself to the root: <code class="mono text-fips-accent"
          >[self, parent, ..., root]</code
        >. Because the tree is rooted and parents are unique, this coordinate uniquely identifies a
        node's position in the tree.
      </p>

      <p>
        Tree distance between two nodes is the total hops from each to their lowest common ancestor.
        This is computed by finding the longest common suffix of their coordinate arrays.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Simulator</h2>

      <p>
        Drag nodes to reposition them. Click a node to inspect it. Use "Route From" to select a
        source, then click a destination to visualize the greedy routing path. "Kill Link" severs a
        random mesh link and the tree reconverges.
      </p>

      <MeshSimulator client:visible />

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Bloom filters for reachability</h2>

      <p>
        Each node maintains a bloom filter that summarizes the set of <code
          class="mono text-fips-accent">node_addr</code
        > values reachable through it. When a node receives a packet for an unknown destination, it queries
        each peer's bloom filter. A "no" answer means the destination is definitely unreachable through
        that peer. A "yes" means the destination might be reachable (bloom filters have false positives,
        but never false negatives).
      </p>

      <p>
        Bloom filters use split-horizon: a node does not include addresses learned from a peer in
        the filter it sends back to that peer. This prevents routing loops.
      </p>

      <p>
        The widget below uses the same ten demo nodes as the simulator above. Each label hashes to a <code
          class="mono text-fips-accent">node_addr</code
        >, which is what actually lands in the filter. Insert a few, then query a node you never
        inserted. Most will come back "definitely not present"; a few will come back "maybe present"
        even though they were never added. That is a false positive.
      </p>

      <BloomFilterViz client:visible />

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">The routing priority chain</h2>

      <p>
        When a node needs to forward a packet, it runs through <code class="mono text-fips-accent"
          >find_next_hop()</code
        >, which follows this priority chain:
      </p>

      <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Local delivery.</strong> Is the destination me? Deliver locally.</li>
        <li><strong>Direct peer.</strong> Is the destination a direct peer? Forward to it.</li>
        <li>
          <strong>Bloom filter candidate.</strong> Does any peer's bloom filter claim reachability? Forward
          to the closest such peer by tree distance.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Greedy tree routing.</strong> Forward to the peer that minimizes tree distance to the
          destination's coordinates.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Backtrack.</strong> Forward to the parent (toward the root), hoping a higher-up node
          has better information.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        The step-through below implements a simplified version (without bloom filter lookup) on a
        five-node mesh. Pick a source and destination, then step through the decision process.
      </p>

      <RoutingDemo client:visible />

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">What happens when the network splits</h2>

      <p>
        If a partition separates the mesh into two (or more) disconnected segments, each segment
        independently reconverges. The segment without the original root elects a new root (the
        smallest <code class="mono text-fips-accent">node_addr</code> in the segment). When segments rejoin,
        the globally smallest root wins, and the tree re-stabilizes.
      </p>

      <p>
        This reconvergence happens through normal gossip. Nodes periodically exchange their root and
        depth information with peers. When the numbers disagree, they re-evaluate their parent
        choices. The process converges in O(diameter) rounds, proportional to the depth of the tree.
      </p>
    </section>

    <Quiz client:visible questions={getQuiz("5-spanning-tree")} title="Routing Quiz" />

    <SeeAlso terms={["spanning-tree", "coordinate", "node_addr", "bloom-filter"]} />
    <LessonNav current={5} />
  </article>
</Base>
